

# Master Extraction Prompt — Collections & Security Package Review

Below is a prompt you can paste directly into **Copilot** (or any document-grounded LLM). Swap the bracketed placeholder at the top for each transaction's document set.

---

## Prompt

> **Context & Role**
>
> You are a structured finance analyst conducting an operational‑resilience review of a lending / private securitisation transaction. You have been given the transaction documents for **[INSERT TRANSACTION NAME / DEAL ID]**. These may include (but are not limited to): the Credit / Facility Agreement, Servicing Agreement, Security Deed / Agreement, Account Bank Agreement, Collections Account Agreement, Intercreditor Agreement, Account Control Agreement (or Account Charge), Power of Attorney, Deed of Assignment, Portfolio Sale provisions, any Side Letters, and ancillary schedules or notices.
>
> **Your task is to search every document in scope and answer each of the questions below with precise references (document name, clause / section number, and a short direct quote where possible). Where the documents are silent or ambiguous, say so explicitly.**
>
> ---
>
> ### QUESTION 1 — Segregated Collection Accounts
>
> a) Does the transaction require a **dedicated / segregated collections account** (i.e., an account used exclusively to receive borrower / obligor collections relating to the financed portfolio, separate from the borrower's or originator's general operating accounts)?
>
> b) If yes:
> - Who is the **account holder** (borrower SPV, originator, SPG entity, other)?
> - At which **bank** is the account held, and is that bank a party to or on notice of the security?
> - Is there an **Account Control Agreement, Account Charge, or equivalent** granting the lender (or its agent/trustee) control or a fixed charge over the account?
> - Are there any **permitted withdrawals or commingling rights** that could dilute the ring‑fencing (e.g., the borrower may sweep funds to a general account after a waterfall test)?
>
> c) If **no** segregated account exists:
> - Where do collections land (originator operating account, client account, other)?
> - Is there any **tracing, earmarking, or trust mechanism** over those receipts in favour of the lender?
>
> ---
>
> ### QUESTION 2 — Visibility into Collections Accounts
>
> For every account into which borrower / portfolio collections are paid:
>
> a) Does **SPG (the lender or its servicer)** have **direct, independent, real‑time or periodic electronic access** to view balances and transaction‑level activity on the collections account(s) — without needing to contact any third party? *(This would be classified as "Free & clear access." Note: having to email or call a custodian is still considered free & clear.)*
>
> b) If SPG does **not** have direct access, does it obtain account information **via an agent bank, account bank, trustee, or other intermediary** who is contractually obligated to provide it — without requiring the client's / borrower's permission? *(This would be classified as "Reliant on 3rd party.")*
>
> c) If neither (a) nor (b), does SPG require the **client's / borrower's consent or cooperation** to obtain visibility over account activity? *(This would be classified as "Reliant on client.")*
>
> d) Cite the specific clauses that establish the reporting, access, or information‑sharing obligations for each account. Note any **frequency** (daily, weekly, monthly), **format** (portal, bank statements, data tape), and any **conditions or triggers** that change the access level (e.g., access upgrades upon an event of default).
>
> ---
>
> ### QUESTION 3 — Collateral Possession & Control
>
> a) What is the **nature of the collateral** (receivables, loans, leases, physical assets, shares, IP, other)?
>
> b) Has the collateral been **legally assigned, charged, or pledged** to the lender (or a security trustee on its behalf)? Specify whether the assignment/charge is:
> - **Legal (perfected)** or **equitable / beneficial only**;
> - **By way of security** or **by way of true sale**;
> - Whether **notice of assignment** has been given to underlying obligors / debtors.
>
> c) In a **servicer‑transfer scenario** (i.e., the current servicer is replaced), can SPG (or its appointed successor servicer) **access and take operational control of the collateral and all related data, records, and systems without the client's / borrower's cooperation**?
> - If yes — state the mechanism (e.g., step‑in rights, power of attorney, back‑up servicer appointment, data escrow). *(Classify as: "Collateral owned or assigned to borrower; SPG has access in case of servicer transfer or portfolio sale.")*
> - If access is achievable **through a third party** (e.g., back‑up servicer, data trustee, custodian) **without reliance on the client** — state the mechanism. *(Classify as: "Collateral accessible via 3rd party without reliance on client.")*
> - If the client's / borrower's **active cooperation is required** to effect the transfer — state what is needed and why. *(Classify as: "Reliance on client necessary.")*
>
> d) In a **portfolio‑sale scenario** (SPG sells or transfers its interest in the financed portfolio to a third‑party purchaser):
> - Can this be effected **without client consent**?
> - Are there any **consent rights, pre‑emption rights, or transfer restrictions** in favour of the borrower / originator?
> - Apply the same three‑tier classification as above.
>
> e) Where is the **loan / collateral documentation physically or electronically held** (custodian, solicitor's undertaking, SPG's own systems, client's systems)? Does SPG or its security trustee hold originals or certified copies?
>
> ---
>
> ### QUESTION 4 — Additional / Noteworthy Items
>
> Flag anything else that is relevant to SPG's operational resilience and control posture over this transaction, including but not limited to:
>
> - Any **waterfall or cash‑management** mechanics that could delay or redirect collections before they reach SPG;
> - Any **commingling risk** windows (e.g., collections sit in a non‑segregated account for X days before sweep);
> - Any **set‑off risk** (collections account at a bank to which the borrower owes money);
> - Any **delegation or sub‑servicing** arrangements that add intermediary layers;
> - Any **cure or remedy periods** before SPG can exercise step‑in or enforcement rights;
> - Any **jurisdictional or regulatory constraints** (e.g., local law requirements for account location, data‑protection restrictions on transferring borrower data);
> - Any provisions that **change upon an Event of Default or Trigger Event** (e.g., account control flips, reporting frequency increases, standstill periods);
> - Any **gaps or weaknesses** you identify relative to best practice.
>
> ---
>
> ### OUTPUT FORMAT
>
> Return your findings in the following table structure (one row per transaction / facility, or one row per account if multiple accounts exist):
>
> | Field | Response |
> |---|---|
> | **Transaction / Deal Name** | |
> | **1. Segregated Collection Account?** | Yes / No — [detail] |
> | **2. Visibility into Collections Account** | *Free & clear access* / *Reliant on 3rd party* / *Reliant on client* — [detail & clause refs] |
> | **3. Collateral Possession & Control** | *(i) SPG has access* / *(ii) Accessible via 3rd party* / *(iii) Reliance on client necessary* — [detail & clause refs] |
> | **4. Comments / Noteworthy Items** | [Free text] |
>
> After the table, provide a **"Key Clauses Index"** listing every clause you relied on, grouped by document, so the reviewer can verify quickly.
>
> If any question **cannot be answered** from the documents provided, state clearly: *"NOT ADDRESSED IN DOCUMENTS REVIEWED"* and flag it as a follow‑up item.

---

## How to Use

| Step | Action |
|------|--------|
| **1** | Upload or reference the full document set for the transaction into Copilot's context window (drag PDFs into the chat, or point Copilot at the relevant SharePoint / Teams folder). |
| **2** | Paste the prompt above, replacing **[INSERT TRANSACTION NAME / DEAL ID]**. |
| **3** | Review the output table and the Key Clauses Index. Spot‑check at least the highest‑risk classifications (anything marked *Reliant on client*). |
| **4** | Copy the table row into your consolidated response tracker (the master spreadsheet with the List tab). |
| **5** | Repeat for each transaction. |

> **Tip for large document sets:** If Copilot truncates or misses documents, split the prompt into the four numbered sections and run them sequentially, telling Copilot *"Continue answering from the same documents"* each time.


# Review of developing asset classes/structures: UK second‑lien mortgages

## Executive summary

- The UK second‑lien (“second charge”) mortgage market is a niche but fast‑growing segment of secured consumer lending: new business in the 12 months to November 2025 was **£2,089m across 40,886 agreements** (vs **£1,692m / 35,367** in the 12 months to November 2024, and **£1,385m / 30,411** in the 12 months to November 2023). citeturn20view0turn24search0turn24search14  
- Borrower use‑cases are dominated by **debt consolidation and home improvement** combinations; in November 2025, **58.0%** of new agreements were solely for consolidation, **22.4%** for home improvements + consolidation, and **10.8%** solely for home improvements. citeturn20view0  
- Macroeconomic context supports “rate‑lock” demand (borrowers reluctant to refinance a first mortgage): the entity["organization","Bank of England","uk central bank"]’s **Bank Rate is 3.75% (current)**, with the most recent cut in **December 2025** and previous cuts since **August 2024**. citeturn26view0turn26view1turn26view2  
- Collateral risk is driven by **subordination to the senior mortgage** and realised house prices: the entity["organization","HM Land Registry","land registry, uk"]’s UK HPI (December 2025) reports an average UK house price of **~£270,000** and annual price growth easing to **2.4%** (provisional). citeturn25search0turn25search6  
- Public securitisation exists and is expanding. Example: **Together Asset Backed Securitisation 2025‑2ND1** lists **£276.8m** of notes (Class A–F and Z, with both Reg S and 144A lines shown on entity["organization","Euronext Dublin","stock exchange, dublin, ie"]’s public documents page). citeturn34search0  
- A second example of public issuance in 2025: **Fylde Funding 2025‑1** lists **£204.8m** of notes across Classes A–F plus X1/X2. citeturn31view0  
- Transaction structuring in at least one leading shelf (Together) includes standard UK RMBS protections adapted to second‑ranking collateral: multiple tranches (including non‑collateralised liquidity notes), **25% initial credit enhancement to Class A**, a **liquidity reserve fund**, and **fixed‑to‑floating hedging** where assets include fixed‑rate loans but liabilities reference compounded SONIA. citeturn15view1  
- Data availability remains a key diligence issue. The entity["organization","Financial Conduct Authority","uk financial regulator"]’s published mortgage Product Sales Data (PSD) explicitly notes that **second charge mortgages are not included in the main PSD analysis**, limiting regulator‑published time series for this segment. citeturn21view0turn22view0  

Second‑lien mortgages are conceptually straightforward—an additional legal charge behind a first mortgage—but they are securitisation‑relevant because they combine (i) consumer‑credit‑like borrower motivations (consolidation, liquidity needs) with (ii) property‑secured recoveries that are structurally subordinated to senior debt. The market’s recent growth and increasing public term issuance suggest it is becoming a repeatable “specialist RMBS” funding channel, but it remains a **data‑sparse** sector relative to first‑lien prime RMBS, requiring careful triangulation of originator disclosures, listing documents, and rating‑agency surveillance.

## Asset class overview

**Slide‑ready bullets**

- **Definition**: a mortgage/secured loan where the lender takes a **second‑ranking legal charge** over a residential property already subject to a first charge; recoveries are paid after the first charge is discharged/paid. (Priority treatment is operationally reflected in Land Registry practice around transfers under a chargee’s power of sale and treatment of higher‑priority charges.) citeturn27search1  
- **Typical borrower motivations (observable in market stats)**: debt consolidation dominates; home improvement is the next largest use, often combined with consolidation. citeturn20view0  
- **Observed borrower purpose split (Nov 2025)**: 58.0% consolidation only; 22.4% mixed consolidation + improvements; 10.8% improvements only. citeturn20view0  
- **Origination flow scale**: trailing 12‑month originations rose from **£1,385m (to Nov 2023)** → **£1,692m (to Nov 2024)** → **£2,089m (to Nov 2025)**. citeturn24search14turn24search0turn20view0  
- **Average new‑loan ticket (derived from FLA data)**:
  - 12m to Nov 2023: £1,385m / 30,411 ≈ **£45.5k**  
  - 12m to Nov 2024: £1,692m / 35,367 ≈ **£47.8k**  
  - 12m to Nov 2025: £2,089m / 40,886 ≈ **£51.1k** citeturn24search14turn24search0turn20view0  
- **Product economics (high‑level, evidenced indirectly)**: securitised liabilities reference **compounded SONIA** for at least one major shelf, while assets may include fixed‑rate components, implying active asset/liability management and derivative hedging. citeturn15view1  
- **Regulatory perimeter and conduct**: arrears/forbearance rules in entity["organization","Financial Conduct Authority","uk financial regulator"] mortgage conduct standards materially influence collections strategy and repossession timing (see MCOB 13 requirements referenced in FCA thematic work). citeturn27search8turn27search0  

Second‑lien lending sits between mainstream residential mortgages and secured consumer credit. The clearest, repeatable fact pattern from published market statistics is **purpose**: the segment largely addresses balance‑sheet repair (consolidation) and property investment in the home (improvements). citeturn20view0 The financing logic is often framed as “do not disturb the first mortgage”: when first‑lien refinancing would crystallise a higher rate, a second charge can provide incremental borrowing while leaving the first charge untouched. This macro linkage is consistent with rate conditions and the timing of policy rate cuts from August 2024 onward. citeturn26view0turn26view1  

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  A[Borrower with first mortgage] --> B[Second-lien lender originates second charge]
  B --> C[Second charge registered behind first charge]
  B --> D[Warehouse / term take-out]
  D --> E[SPV purchases receivables]
  E --> F[Notes issued to investors]
  F --> G[Coupon to investors: SONIA-linked liabilities]
  E --> H[Servicer collects borrower payments]
  H --> I[Waterfall: fees -> interest -> principal -> residual]
```
citeturn15view1turn27search1  

## Sector and transaction risk mitigants

**Slide‑ready bullets**

- **Priority/subordination is the core credit risk**: second‑ranking charges sit behind senior mortgages; in a sale under power of sale, the existence of a higher‑priority registered charge can require the transfer to be made **subject to** the senior charge or supported by a **discharge** of that senior charge (and inferior chargees may be notified/cancelled on registration). citeturn27search1  
- **Statutory enforcement toolkit exists (England & Wales)**: a statutory power of sale is implied (once the mortgage money has become due) under **Law of Property Act 1925 s.101**. citeturn27search5  
- **Court discretion in residential possession (England & Wales)**: in possession actions involving a dwelling house, the court may adjourn/suspend/postpone if the borrower is likely to remedy the default within a reasonable period (**Administration of Justice Act 1970 s.36**). This can extend timelines vs purely contractual expectations. citeturn27search2  
- **Conduct and arrears handling are binding constraints**: FCA mortgage arrears rules are explicit that firms must not repossess unless other reasonable attempts have failed (referenced in FCA thematic work on mortgage arrears). citeturn27search8turn27search0  
- **Structural credit enhancement example (Together 2024‑2ND1)**: the structure initially provided **25% credit enhancement to Class A**, via subordination of junior notes. citeturn15view1  
- **Liquidity protection example (Together 2024‑2ND1)**: issuance included non‑collateralised **Class X notes** whose proceeds funded a **liquidity reserve fund (LRF)**. citeturn15view1  
- **Rate/hedging mitigant example (Together 2024‑2ND1)**: fixed‑to‑floating swap against SONIA liabilities, with **entity["company","Natixis S.A.","investment bank, france"]** as swap counterparty (per DBRS disclosure). citeturn15view1  
- **Servicing mitigant examples (Together shelves)**: originator‑servicing with a named standby servicer—**entity["company","BCMGlobal Mortgage Services Limited","servicer, uk"]**—is disclosed in DBRS surveillance and rating action commentary. citeturn15view1turn15view2  

**Table: structural feature comparison (illustrative, from disclosed UK public term deals where available)**

| Feature | Why it matters in second‑lien RMBS | Example disclosure in public sources |
|---|---|---|
| Subordination stack (A–F/Z etc.) | Absorbs losses arising from “thin equity” after senior mortgage pay‑off | Multiple tranches described in Together 2024‑2ND1 (Class A–F, Z, plus liquidity notes). citeturn15view1 |
| Initial credit enhancement to senior | Quantifies cushion vs stress defaults/house price declines | 25% CE to Class A described for Together 2024‑2ND1. citeturn15view1 |
| Liquidity reserve fund (LRF) | Mitigates short‑term payment interruption (delinquencies/servicing disruption) | LRF funded at closing via non‑collateralised Class X proceeds (Together 2024‑2ND1). citeturn15view1 |
| Fixed/float swap / basis risk management | Second‑lien pools may include fixed‑rate products; liabilities generally float (SONIA) | Fixed‑to‑floating swap described in Together 2024‑2ND1. citeturn15view1 |
| Standby servicer | Operational continuity; reduces tail risk from servicer failure | BCMGlobal named as standby servicer in Together 2024‑2ND1 and referenced in 2022‑2ND1 surveillance. citeturn15view1turn15view2 |
| Enforcement reality (E&W) | Second‑lien enforcement depends on statutory powers, court discretion, and priority mechanics | LPA 1925 s.101; AJA 1970 s.36; Land Registry PG75 on power‑of‑sale registration. citeturn27search5turn27search2turn27search1 |
| Repossession as last resort (conduct) | Affects collection timing and loss severity (arrears capitalisation, timeline) | FCA MCOB 13 referenced in FCA TR18/5; rule framing reiterated in FCA policy materials. citeturn27search8turn27search11 |

Second‑lien securitisations look structurally similar to UK specialist RMBS but should be analysed with a “priority‑first” mindset: the **first mortgage balance and its arrears status are effectively a structural senior claim** on collateral proceeds. Operationally, this comes through in how transfers under a power of sale must address higher‑priority charges, and in the reality that the second‑lien lender’s economic recovery may be highly sensitive to small house‑price moves when combined leverage is high. citeturn27search1turn25search0  

From a noteholder perspective, disclosed structures demonstrate that arrangers and CRAs apply familiar mitigants—subordination, liquidity reserves, hedging, standby servicing—and make them explicit in public disclosures, e.g., Together 2024‑2ND1’s 25% senior CE and LRF funding via Class X, plus hedging against SONIA liabilities. citeturn15view1  

## Market backdrop

**Slide‑ready bullets**

- **Policy rate**: Bank Rate is **3.75%** (current), with the most recent change on **18 December 2025**; prior cuts occurred from **August 2024** onward. citeturn26view0turn26view1  
- **Central bank guidance**: the Bank of England’s explainer (updated **12 February 2026**) states it expects scope for further rate cuts in 2026 if the economy evolves as expected, while emphasising uncertainty in timing/magnitude. citeturn26view1  
- **Inflation**: CPI inflation was **3.0% in the 12 months to January 2026** (down from 3.4% in December 2025). citeturn25search10turn25search4  
- **House prices** (December 2025 UK HPI): average UK price **~£270,000**; annual growth **2.4%** (provisional), down from 2.8% in November 2025 (revised). citeturn25search0  
- **Regional nuance**: England annual growth **1.7%**, while London shows **‑1.0%** (12 months to December 2025). citeturn25search9turn25search0  
- **Consumer credit**: annual growth rate for all consumer credit **8.2%** in December 2025; credit card borrowing growth **12.4%**. citeturn25search2  
- **Second‑charge demand linkage (observable)**: FLA commentary explicitly frames 2024–2025 growth against interest‑rate and confidence backdrops, with strong year‑on‑year increases in both volumes and values. citeturn20view0turn24search0  

The macro picture is mixed but directionally supportive for secured‑loan demand. Policy rates have moved down from peaks, but remain elevated; inflation is easing yet still above target. citeturn26view0turn25search10 For second charges, the most directly measurable linkage is through consumer balance‑sheet pressure and refinancing dynamics: growing consumer credit (including credit cards) and a market dominated by consolidation‑purpose lending provide a coherent narrative for continued origination volumes. citeturn25search2turn20view0  

House prices remain positive on a national basis but show regional dispersion (notably London’s negative annual print), which matters because second‑lien recoveries are structurally “equity‑thin” in high combined‑LTV cases. citeturn25search9turn27search1  

## Market size estimate

**Slide‑ready bullets**

- **Primary observable market‑size proxy (annual originations)**: FLA monthly statistics provide a consistent “new business value” and “new agreements” series for the second charge mortgage market. citeturn20view0turn24search0turn24search14  
- **Latest trailing‑12 originations (12m to Nov 2025)**: **£2,089m** and **40,886** agreements. citeturn20view0  
- **Time series (aligned 12m to Nov endpoints)**:
  - 12m to Nov 2023: **£1,385m**, 30,411 agreements  
  - 12m to Nov 2024: **£1,692m**, 35,367 agreements  
  - 12m to Nov 2025: **£2,089m**, 40,886 agreements citeturn24search14turn24search0turn20view0  
- **Derived average new‑loan size** rose from ~£45.5k (12m to Nov 2023) to ~£51.1k (12m to Nov 2025), calculated as value ÷ agreements. citeturn24search14turn20view0  
- **Outstanding balance**: no single authoritative public series was identified in this research run. FCA PSD publishes mortgage sales but explicitly excludes second charge mortgages from main analysis; this constrains regulator‑published aggregates. citeturn21view0turn22view0  
- **Methodology for an indicative outstanding estimate (stock‑flow model)**:
  - Step 1: take an originations proxy (e.g., average annual new business over 2023–2025 endpoints).  
  - Step 2: assume an average life/tenor in years (high uncertainty without public run‑off data).  
  - Step 3: Outstanding ≈ Flow × Average Life.  
  This is a modelling approach, not a confirmed statistic; see confidence ranges below. citeturn24search14turn24search0turn20view0  
- **Data gaps to close for investment‑grade sizing**: obtain (i) lender regulatory returns that explicitly separate second‑charge balances, and/or (ii) commercial datasets (e.g., Dealogic/Refinitiv) to aggregate originator balance sheets and securitised + warehouse outstandings. (Not available within cited public sources here.) citeturn21view0  

**Table: originations and derived average ticket (from FLA; calculations shown)**

| Trailing 12 months to… | New business value (£m) | New agreements | Derived average loan (£k) | Calculation |
|---|---:|---:|---:|---|
| Nov 2023 | 1,385 | 30,411 | 45.5 | 1,385,000,000 ÷ 30,411 |
| Nov 2024 | 1,692 | 35,367 | 47.8 | 1,692,000,000 ÷ 35,367 |
| Nov 2025 | 2,089 | 40,886 | 51.1 | 2,089,000,000 ÷ 40,886 |

